metadata.name: Midfile Crisis #96
metadata.description:
Midfile Crisis is about realizing halfway through you are not gonna make it.

The struggle is real.

-

The work itself is the union of 2 projects, which, well, didn’t make it. Together though, they are stronger than ever. So yes, Midfile Crisis is a love story, too.

-

Procedural , ever changing real-time animation, October 2022
Javascript and WebGL

-

FEATURES

- 6 color palettes, inspired by recent artworks by Xenia Hausner, Ayako Rokkaku, Jenny Saville, Amy Sherald, Sue Williams and Emily Xie, are referenced accordingly. One additional, rare color palette will slowly cycle through the full color spectrum.
- Direction: Up, Right, Up Right
- Seed: Up, Right, Up Left
- Shape Tendency: Tetra, Box, Sphere, Octa, Ico, Multi
- Amount: Low, Medium, High

VIEWING

- The artwork is in landscape format, please click on open to see the full frame and resolution. We recommend rotating your screen on mobile.
- Press 'i' to show artwork title and features.
- Press 's' to save an image.
- To guarantee the same output at different resolutions the simulation driving the artwork is locked at 1024x512 pixels. To unlock, press 'u' - this can help when running at a lower resolution and the animation is not smooth, or when running at significanly higher resolutions and pixelation is starting to occur. Please note this will break the deterministic nature of the work.
- Best viewed in Chrome Desktop with dedicated GPU.
- Please note: requires latest devices (supporting WebGL2) for a smooth experience.

metadata.name: Ordinary Places #269
metadata.description:
“Ordinary Places” is a fully-coded meditation on the poetic beauty of everyday landscapes. 

The architectural characters in these landscapes include water towers (inspired by Bernd & Hilla Becher’s “Water Tower” photography series), gas stations (inspired by Ed Ruscha’s “26 Gasoline Stations” photography book), and barns (inspired by childhood memories on my grandfather’s farm). 

Yet, while these scenes may seem ordinary upon first glance, something darker lurks beneath the surface. The hidden secrets of these Ordinary Places can only be revealed through the minting process. In this sense, the outputs are not merely a collection individual scenes, but instead, a coherent world animated by shared themes and narratives.     

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Uninhabitable #192
metadata.description:
Uninhabitable is a generative system built only from ellipses. The process of playing with different geometric and trigonometric disruptions gives rise to four different compositions which seek to evoque living constructions and environments. Besides the shape itself and its related distortion, the stroke weight of the lines plays a meaningful role in the piece. Following a discrete range [0.01,0.1,1] the weight reveals the process allowing the viewer to realize the trace of the huge amount of lines in each piece. This back and forth between scales and context is, while kind of stripping the code, part of my continuing interest on understanding the -usually- crazy paths of machines' way of thinking.

Press "h" to see it and high resolution and refresh to get back to the initial state. Press "h" to save it.

Uninhabitable is an original work by Iskra Velitchkova. 2021.

metadata.name: Southern Gothic #236
metadata.description:
“Southern Gothic” is my debut release on the fxhash platform. The project is created entirely through code. All copyrights are released to the holder of each image output, even for commercial purposes.

“Southern Gothic” borrows its name from the literary genre made famous by writers like Flannery O’Connor and Carson McCullers. Rather than illustrating a singular setting, the code generates an entire rural townscape, thereby, blurring the boundaries between representation and narrative. The individual scenes are framed frontally with an intentionally flat aesthetic character, referencing traditional folk art of the American South. The absence of human figures within these scenes adds to their overwhelming sense of darkness and forlorn. Observing multiple scenes side-by-side, one may even get the strange feeling that something terrible has happened (or is about to happen) in this rural landscape.

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Charcoal Landscapes #69
metadata.description:
This work is an exploration of abstract landscapes using lines that are bounded to 8 directions. This limitation still allows for somewhat organic visuals and creates a visual language more akin to traditional drawing techniques.

Using a vector field with a noise function at different scales, I construct paths starting at random positions and moving to the neighbours cells pointed at by the vector field. Paths have a limitation of length and are bounded to the grid. I create tens of thousands of paths then render progressively on screen.

There are 10 parameters variations and 4 colors, 2 being rare and one very rare.

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2021

metadata.name: September #303
metadata.description:
The Summer Ends
---------------
Controls:
S or double tap (mobile): Download image

A: Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)

1-6: Modify scale (1 = default, 1500 x 2000px, 6 = maximum, 9000 x 12000px (performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F: Fit to current screen size

T: Toggle grain and texture overlay
H: Toggle shape outlines

B: Cycle border sizes (0 -> 50 -> 75 -> 100 -> 150px)
C: Cycle border colors

I: Cycle visible layers

L: Toggle “live mode”. This mode will continuously redraw a new output every few seconds using the same base parameters as the original output, but with slight variations.

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)
---------------

metadata.name: Calmer waters - reissue #5
metadata.description:
This is a reissue of project #10669
https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/10669

I long for calmer waters. This piece is about that. It's a counterpoint. It reflects some of my best memories of the sea: the warm salty air on my face, interspersed with a cool breeze, leaving my lips salty tasting. The gentle rushing of the water. 

The sea with its vast panorama's can make you feel insignificant in the grand scheme of things. But this piece is about hope.
///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
About this reissue: An update of the security policy of fx(hash) blocks external scripts. This update stops malicious actors; they could try to interact with a user’s wallet. So, this update is really a good thing. It’s a safeguard. However, due to this update the original project no longer loads in live view and after consultation and deliberation I decided to reissue the token without the use of external scripts (p5js). 

Only holders of the original project are on the allow list. 

Royalties are for the minter.

metadata.description:
"I shall be telling this with a sigh
Somewhere ages and ages hence:
Two roads diverged in a wood, and I—
I took the one less traveled by,
And that has made all the difference."

- Robert Frost, The Road Not Taken



=========

Controls:
[1] set resolution to 1024x1024 (default)
[2] set resolution to 2048x2048 
[3] set resolution to 4096x4096
[0] set resolution to window size (might help on lower end computers)

[c] capture a screenshot at rendered resolution


Made with cables.gl, a node-based webgl environment
XALTED 2022
